WAR ROOM — CURSOR RULES
These rules apply to all work in this repository.

PROJECT CONTEXT
This is "The War Room" — a multi-model adversarial debate system for QA testing productivity apps.
Built at the 2026 yconic New England Inter-Collegiate AI Hackathon by Tucker Anglemyer & Griffin Kovach.
Stack: CrewAI, ChromaDB, FastAPI, React, NVIDIA DGX Spark.

GIT COMMIT RULES — CRITICAL (repo is graded by AI every 15 minutes)

Commit Message Format
Always use Conventional Commits format:
  feat: <description>      — New feature or capability
  fix: <description>       — Bug fix
  refactor: <description>  — Code restructuring without behavior change
  docs: <description>      — Documentation updates
  chore: <description>     — Tooling, config, dependencies
  test: <description>      — Adding or updating tests
  style: <description>     — Formatting, no logic change
  perf: <description>      — Performance improvement

Commit Message Quality
- Messages MUST be specific and descriptive. Never use generic messages like "update files" or "fix stuff"
- Reference the component being changed: "feat(crew): add context chaining for 4-round debate"
- If multiple things changed, break into multiple commits
- Good: "feat(meta-prompt): add dynamic persona generation with JSON parsing and static fallback"
- Good: "fix(crew): resolve context propagation between Round 2 and Round 3 tasks"
- Good: "feat(tools): wire search_app_reviews to ChromaDB app_reviews collection"
- Good: "docs(readme): add architecture diagram and debate structure explanation"
- Good: "refactor(crew): extract LLM config to environment variables for DGX swap"
- Good: "perf(meta-prompt): reduce token usage by tightening persona generation prompt"
- Bad: "update crew.py"
- Bad: "fix bug"
- Bad: "changes"

Commit Frequency
- Commit after every meaningful change — small, frequent commits show professional workflow
- Never bundle unrelated changes in one commit
- A working feature = immediate commit + push

Auto-Push Workflow
Whenever I ask you to "push", "git push", "gp", "push it", "send it", "ship it", or any variation:
1. Run git add .
2. Generate a high-quality conventional commit message based on what actually changed (check git diff --cached)
3. Run git commit -m "<your generated message>"
4. Run git push
5. Confirm with the commit message used

If nothing changed, say "Nothing to push — working tree is clean."

CODE QUALITY RULES

Python
- Use type hints on all function signatures
- Add docstrings to all public functions
- Keep functions under 50 lines — extract helpers
- Use descriptive variable names, never single letters except loop counters
- Handle errors gracefully with try/except and meaningful error messages
- Follow PEP 8 formatting

File Organization
- One concern per file: crew.py for orchestration, tools.py for RAG tools, meta_prompt.py for persona generation
- Keep imports organized: stdlib, third-party, local
- Configuration values (model names, URLs, collection names) at the top of files as constants

Documentation
- README.md must always reflect current state of the project
- Update README when adding features, changing architecture, or adding setup steps
- Include code comments explaining WHY, not WHAT (the code shows what)

ARCHITECTURE REFERENCE
- meta_prompt.py — Generates 3 dynamic adversarial personas via LLM before crew runs
- crew.py — CrewAI sequential crew: 4 rounds, 3 agents, context chaining
- tools.py — 6 RAG tool stubs for ChromaDB (Griffin connects these)
- requirements.txt — Python dependencies
- Future: api.py — FastAPI + WebSocket for streaming debate to frontend
- Future: frontend/ — React + Tailwind debate visualization

DGX SWAP NOTES
When switching from local dev to DGX Spark:
- Replace local_llm in crew.py with 3 separate LLM instances pointing at different models
  - Llama 3.3-70B → First-Timer (port 8001 if using vLLM)
  - Qwen3-32B → Daily Driver (port 8002 if using vLLM)
  - Mistral-Small-24B → Buyer (port 8003 if using vLLM)
- Or use Ollama with model names: ollama/llama3.3:70b, ollama/qwen3:32b, ollama/mistral-small:24b
